{{lowercase}}
'''mChip''' is a [[Point-of-care testing|portable blood test device]] which is capable of [[Diagnosis|diagnosing]] an [[infection]] of [[HIV]] or [[Syphilis]]<ref name=post>{{cite news|title=Rapid, cheap HIV test finds success as first of its kind tested in the field|first=Torres|last=Christian|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/rapid-cheap-hiv-test-finds-success-as-first-of-its-kind-tested-in-the-field/2011/07/27/gIQAUo1dlI_story.html|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=July 31, 2011|accessdate=Aug 09, 2011}}</ref><ref name=nature>{{cite journal|last1=Chin|first1=Curtis D|last2=Laksanasopin|first2=Tassaneewan|last3=Cheung|first3=Yuk Kee|last4=Cheung|first4=Yuk Kee|last5=Steinmiller|first5=David|last6=Linder|first6=Vincent|last7=Parsa|first7=Hesam|last8=Wang|first8=Jennifer|last9=Moore|first9=Hannah|last10=Rouse|first10=Robert|last11=Umviligihozo|first11=Gisele|last12=Karita|first12=Etienne|last13=Mwambarangwe|first13=Lambert|last14=Braunstein|first14=Sarah L|last15=van de Wijgert|first15=Janneke|last16=Sahabo|first16=Ruben|last17=Justman|first17=Jessica E|last18=El-Sadr|first18=Wafaa|last19=Sia|first19=Samuel K |date=31 July 2011 |title=Microfluidics-based diagnostics of infectious diseases in the developing world|journal=NATURE MEDICINE|volume=17|issue=1|pages=1015–1019|publisher=Nature Journal|doi=10.1038/nm.2408|issn=1078-8956|url=http://www.nature.com/nm/journal/v17/n8/full/nm.2408.html|accessdate=2011-07-20}}</ref> within 15 minutes<ref name=voa/> and could be used effectively against [[HIV/AIDS]] in developing countries.<ref name=post/><ref name=voa>{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/english/news/health/New-Portable-Device-Diagnoses-HIV-Syphilis-126617333.html|title=New Portable Device Diagnoses HIV, Syphilis|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|accessdate=2011-08-09|work=}}</ref><ref name=times>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-08-08/science/29864031_1_hiv-blood-credit-card|title=$1 tiny chip tests blood, detects HIV in 15 min|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=2011-08-09|work=|date=2011-08-08}}</ref> The mChip costs about [[US$]] 1<ref name=voa/> and the entire diagnostic kit costs about [[US$]] 100.<ref name=voa/><ref name=exame/> mChip was developed so that people in regions with poor health facilities can access portable diagnosis for [[HIV/AIDS]] rather than travelling long distances to go to clinics for diagnosis.<ref name=times/>

==Background==
[[Lateral flow test]] is one of the blood testing methods used, in which a [[Venipuncture|blood sample]] or [[Forensic toxicology#Oral fluid|oral fluid]] is placed on a strip of paper. In this method, a colored band indicates [[infection]]. Lateral flow tests are generally considered to be unreliable.<ref name=post/>

People in lesser developed regions like the [[Sub-Saharan Africa]] are adversely affected by [[HIV/AIDS]] and have very limited access to [[Medical laboratory|clinical labs]] or [[hospital]]s. There have been estimates which indicate that there are about 22.5 million people suffering from [[HIV/AIDS]] in such regions and hence there is a high demand for [[Point-of-care testing|portable blood test device]]s.<ref name=wallstreet>{{cite web|url=http://www.wallstreetdaily.com/2011/08/05/mchip-hiv-test/|title=How This 15-Minute Test Could Save Millions of Lives|publisher=Wall street Daily|accessdate=2011-08-09|work=}}</ref> Hence devices like mChip will be able to diagnose [[HIV/AIDS]] in such regions

==Development==
mChip was developed by scientists at [[Columbia University]]<ref name=big5>{{cite web|url=http://big5.xinhuanet.com/gate/big5/news.xinhuanet.com/photo/2011-08/08/c_121827551.htm|title=US-developed HIV rapid test device only 15 minutes|publisher=big5.xinhuanet.com|language=Chinese|accessdate=2011-08-09|work=}}</ref> in [[New York]]. Initial testing of this device was undertaken in a village in [[Rwanda]],<ref name=nature/><ref name=medicalfacts>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicalfacts.nl/2011/08/08/snelle-en-goedkope-diagnostiek-voor-de-derde-wereld/|title=Rapid and inexpensive diagnostics for the Third World|publisher=medicalfacts.nl|language=Dutch|accessdate=2011-08-09|work=}}</ref> where, according to the [[World Health Organization]], approximately 3 percent of the population suffers from [[HIV/AIDS]].<ref name=post/> Of the 400 volunteers who turned up for testing, 399 were correctly diagnosed with an accuracy of nearly 100 percent.<ref name=big5/><ref name=notizie>{{cite web|url=http://notizie.tiscali.it/articoli/scienza/11/08/01/mchip-mini-laboratorio-analisi-sangue.html|title=MChip arrives, mini-lab for blood tests DIY|publisher=notizie.tiscali.it|language=Italian|accessdate=2011-08-09|work=}}</ref><ref name=eatg>{{cite web|url=http://www.eatg.org/eatg/Global-HIV-News/Prevention/Field-trials-of-rapid-inexpensive-and-portable-HIV-test-show-success-researchers-report|title=Field trials of rapid, inexpensive and portable HIV test show success, researchers report|publisher=European AIDS Treatment Group|accessdate=2011-08-09|work=}}</ref><ref name=globalhealth>{{cite web|url=http://globalhealth.kff.org/Daily-Reports/2011/August/01/GH-080111-mChip-HIV-Test.aspx|title=Field Trials Of Rapid, Inexpensive And Portable HIV Test Show Success, Researchers Report|publisher=US Global health policy|accessdate=2011-08-09|work=}}</ref> mChip was also tested for its effectiveness in diagnosing [[syphilis]], where, out of the 67 volunteers who turned up for testing, 63 were correctly diagnosed with an accuracy of nearly 94 percent.<ref name=post/><ref name=voa/> The appearance of mChip resembles a [[credit card]].<ref name=post/><ref name=exame>{{cite web|url=http://exame.abril.com.br/tecnologia/ciencia/noticias/chip-de-us-1-detecta-hiv-com-gota-de-sangue|title=$ 1 Chip detects HIV in blood drop|publisher=exame.abril.com.br|language=Portuguese|accessdate=2011-08-09|work=}}</ref> and is estimated to cost just [[US$]] 1.<ref name=voa/>

==Operation==
The operation of mChip is similar to that of [[ELISA]] (Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay).<ref name=nature/> The ELISA can be performed to evaluate either the presence of antigen or the presence of antibody in a sample. It is a useful tool for determining [[blood plasma|serum]] antibody concentrations such as with the [[HIV test]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003538.htm|title=ELISA/Western blot tests for HIV|publisher=Medline Plus|accessdate=2011-08-16|work=}}</ref> The mChip contains 10 zones<ref name=exame/> which detect the passage of a small amount (about 1μl) of blood.<ref name=nature/> The results can be obtained in a color-coded format<ref name=times/> in about 15 minutes.<ref name=exame/>

